declare(strict_types=1);

namespace Drupal\example\Controller;

use Drupal\Core\Controller\ControllerBase;

class ExampleController extends ControllerBase {

  public function exampleAction(): array {
    // Using named arguments safely
    $this->messenger()->addMessage(
      message: 'Configuration imported successfully.',
      type: 'status',
      repeat: FALSE,
    );

    return [
      '#markup' => $this->t('Example page.'),
    ];
  }

}
```

✅ Named arguments improve readability and prevent positional errors.
✅ `type:` must be one of: `'status'`, `'warning'`, `'error'` (string).
✅ `repeat: FALSE` suppresses duplicate messages.

⚠️ `drupal_set_message()` is legacy; prefer the `messenger()` service in Drupal 9+:

```php
$container->get('messenger')->addMessage(...);
```

In `services.yml`, use:
```yaml
arguments:
  $messenger: '@messenger'
```

And inject it via constructor:
```php
public function __construct(private MessengerInterface $messenger) {}
```

In Drupal 11 with PHP 8.3, use **constructor property promotion** with `readonly` and explicit type hints to enforce immutability and type safety.

Example service class:
```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace Drupal\my_module\Service;

use Drupal\Core\Database\Connection;
use Drupal\Core\Config\ConfigFactoryInterface;

final class MyService {
  public function __construct(
    private readonly Connection $database,
    private readonly ConfigFactoryInterface $configFactory,
    private readonly string $moduleConfigName
  ) {
    // No body needed — properties are promoted and readonly
  }

  public function doWork(): array {
    // Safe: readonly ensures properties cannot be reassigned
    $config = $this->configFactory->get($this->moduleConfigName);
