Example 1: Use `#[Service]` on a plugin class that implements `ContainerAwareInterface`:

```php
<?php

declare(strict_types=1);

namespace Drupal\my_module\Plugin\Action;

use Drupal\Core\Action\ActionBase;
use Drupal\Core\DependencyInjection\ContainerAwareInterface;
use Symfony\Component\DependencyInjection\Attribute\Autowired;
use Symfony\Component\DependencyInjection\Attribute\Service;

#[Service(id: 'my_module.custom_action')]
class CustomAction extends ActionBase implements ContainerAwareInterface {
  #[Autowired]
  private \Drupal\Core\Database\Connection $database;

  #[Autowired]
  private \Psr\Log\LoggerInterface $logger;

  public function execute($entity = null): void {
    $this->logger->notice('Action executed on entity ID: {id}', ['{id}' => $entity->id()]);
  }
}
```

Example 2: Use `#[AsRole]` for test-specific tagging (e.g., in `KernelTest`):

```php
#[AsRole('admin')]
class AdminTest extends KernelTestBase {
  // ...
}
```

⚠️ **Critical**:
- Attributes like `#[Service]`, `#[Autowired]`, and `#[AsRole]` are *Symfony* attributes — not Drupal plugin annotations
- Plugin annotations (`@Plugin`, `@views\plugin`) are still parsed via `phpdoc` — attributes *do not replace* them in core plugin discovery
- For service definitions, prefer attributes over YAML where possible (PHP 8.3+) for type safety and refactoring tools

This ensures clean separation between annotation-based discovery (Drupal) and attribute-based DI (Symfony).

